        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:

From Remijan et al. (2004), the brightest lines of primary target molecules in this survey, namely methyl formate, will be ~100 mJy while others, such as CH3CHN, will be more intense (~1 Jy).  However, other extremely useful molecular tracers, such as ethyl cyanide, vinyl cyanide, and optically-thin 13CH3CN and 13CH3OH, will be much less intense.  Still, the weakest of these will likely of the order of 10-20 mJy.   We have therefore requested a sensitivity of 3.0 mJy to provide the 3-7 sigma detections of these features.  

Prior observations also indicate a linewidth of ~7 km/s.  We have therefore requested a resolution of 1.4 km/s to provide at least 5 resolution elements per FWHM.  This combination of sensitivity and resolution will provide the necessary information to extract robust lineshape parameters from the lines for use in determining temperatures and abundances.

Prior low-sensitivity maps of the region by Remijan et al. (2004) show target molecular source sizes of ~5", with O/N differentiation on the scale of ~3".  We have therefore requested an angular resolution of 0.5".  At this resolution, we are sensitive to the ~5" extended structure of the source, while still having a synthesized beam which is reasonably well-matched to the compact source size.  The requested sensitivity levels provide a sufficient buffer in the case of any flux which may be resolved out by the narrow beam.

Imaging:

The spatial separation of the O/N cores outlined in the Scientific Justification is ~2.7" (see Fig 2. of Scientific Justification), with small scale structure suggested on sub-arcsecond scales (Minh et al. 2010).  We have therefore requested an angular resolution of 0.5".  This resolution makes ideal and efficient use of ALMA resources by 1) providing more than five times the spatial resolution across this differentiation region, 2) not requiring use of the ACA to recover the large-scale structure, and 3) requiring only a single 12-m configuration for these observations.  The target sources (~5") easily fit within the primary beam of the array (26"), so we anticipate no issues with sensitivity loss. The UV coverage of the region will be robust over the course of the on-source integration.

Correlator Setup:

As outlined in the Scientific Justification, we have chosen to target a 15 GHz region of the spectrum for a spectral scan at 1.4 km/s resolution.  A simulation of several of the key target species in this spectral region is shown in Figure 3 of the Scientific Justification.  This window provides an ideal mix of strong molecular transitions covering a broad range of upper state energies from 30 K to more than 1000 K.  This will allow for a robust constraint of excitation conditions and abundances in the region - essential factors in the determination of the evolutionary causes of O/N differentiation.  As stated above, the sensitivity and resolution will provide the necessary information to extract robust lineshape parameters from the lines for use in determining these conditions and abundances.

Calibration:

We have selected system-defined calibration as suggested.

Bandpass accuracy:

We anticipate no issues arising in this area, as the targeted features are narrow and intense.  In addition, a member of the observing team helped commission the spectral line observing mode for the observatory

Scheduling/Time Constraints:

We require no special scheduling or time considerations.

Data rate:

We do not exceed the recommended data rate for these observations.

Special constraints:

Our total overheads constitute &lt;25% of the total observational time and have moderate integration times.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
